{"title_page": "Tall Ships America", "text_new": "{{Update|inaccurate=yes|article|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name           = Tall Ships America (American Sail Training Association)\n| logo           = Tall Ships America.png\n| type           = 501(c)(3) non-profit organization\n| foundation     = [[Rhode Island]] (April 1, 1973)\n| location       = [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport, RI]]\n| key_people     = Dr. Kris Von Wald,PhD, Executive Director.<br>Michael Rauworth, Board Chair.<br>  [[Barclay Harding Warburton III]], founder.\n| industry       = [[Education]] through [[Sail training]]\n| products       = [[Adventure and education under sail]]\n| revenue        = $530,498 [[USD]] ([[Fiscal year|FY]] 2003)\n| homepage       = {{URL|www.sailtraining.org}}\n}}\n\nFounded on April 3, 1973, by [[Barclay Harding Warburton III]], the '''American Sail Training Association''' ('''ASTA'''), now known as '''Tall Ships America''', is currently the largest [[sail training]] association in the world and a founding member of [[Sail Training International#Sail Training International|Sail Training International]].<ref>http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1123698/index.htm{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1983/05/06/obituaries/barclay-warburton-3d-dies-founder-of-tall-ships-group.html</ref>\n\nFrom her humble beginnings with only a handful of vessels sailing the [[New England]] waters, '''Tall Ships America''' has grown into an international institution with more than 250 [[tall ship]]s and [[sail training]] vessels representing 25 different countries and [[navigation|navigating]] all the [[world|world's]] [[ocean]]s.\n\nASTA was created by [[Barclay Harding Warburton III]] following his return from [[The Tall Ships' Races]] in Europe in 1972 where he joined the [[USCGC Eagle (WIX-327)|USCGC ''Eagle'']] with his [[brigantine]] ''Black Pearl'' as the first US vessels to participate in the races.\n\nA 501(c)(3) [[nonprofit]] organization, Tall Ships America's mission is to encourage character building through sail training, promote sail training to the North American public, and support education under sail.\n\n'''Tall Ships America''' organizes the '''[[Tall Ships Challenge|TALL SHIPS CHALLENGE Series]]''', a series of sail training races, rallies and maritime festivals that rotate every three years around the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] and [[Great Lakes]] Coasts of [[North America]]. In 2016, the TALL SHIPS CHALLENGE series is in the Great Lakes. In 2015, the series was on the East Coast with stops in Cape Charles, VA, Philadelphia, PA/Camden, NJ, Greenport, NY and Portland, ME.\n\n==Member ship organizations==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=23em|\n* [[Argo (yacht)]]\n* [[Balclutha (1886)]]\n* [[Bounty (1960 ship)]]\n* [[Californian (schooner)]]\n* [[Corwith Cramer (ship)]]\n* [[ARM Cuauht\u00e9moc (BE01)]]\n* [[KRI Dewaruci]]\n* [[Harvey Gamage (schooner)]]\n* [[Hawaiian Chieftain]]\n* [[Irving Johnson (ship)]]\n* [[Joseph Conrad (ship)]]\n* [[Kaisei (ship)]]\n* [[Lady Washington]]\n* [[Lynx (tall ship)]]\n* [[Ocean Star (schooner)]]\n* [[Picton Castle (ship)]]\n* [[Pilgrim (brig)]]\n* [[Pride of Baltimore]]\n* [[R. Tucker Thompson]]\n* [[Robert C. Seamans (ship)]]\n* [[Roseway(schooner)]]\n* [[Star of India (ship)]]\n* [[Stavros S Niarchos]]\n* [[HMS Surprise (replica ship)]]\n* [[Swift of Ipswich]]\n* [[Tole Mour]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sail training]]\n*[[Seamanship]]\n*[[Tall ship]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* American Sail Training Association; ''Sail Tall Ships!'' (American Sail Training Association; 16th edition, 2005 {{ISBN|0-9636483-9-X}})\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sailtraining.org/ The American Sail Training Association]\n*[http://www.sailtraininginternational.org/ Sail Training International]\n\n<!-- FAIR USE of American Sail Training Association (logo).jpg: see image description page at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:American Sail Training Association (logo).jpg for rationale -->\n\n[[Category:Sail training associations]]\n[[Category:Yachting associations]]\n[[Category:Vessels of the American Sail Training Association| ]]\n[[Category:Educational organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Rhode Island]]\n", "text_old": "{{Update|inaccurate=yes|article|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name           = Tall Ships America (American Sail Training Association)\n| logo           = Tall Ships America.png\n| type           = 501(c)(3) non-profit organization\n| foundation     = [[Rhode Island]] (April 1, 1973)\n| location       = [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport, RI]]\n| key_people     = Dr. Kris Von Wald,PhD, Executive Director.<br>Michael Rauworth, Board Chair.<br>  [[Barclay Harding Warburton III]], founder.\n| industry       = [[Education]] through [[Sail training]]\n| products       = [[Adventure and education under sail]]\n| revenue        = $530,498 [[USD]] ([[Fiscal year|FY]] 2003)\n| homepage       = {{URL|www.sailtraining.org}}\n}}\n\nFounded on April 3, 1973, by [[Barclay Harding Warburton III]], the '''American Sail Training Association''' ('''ASTA'''), now known as '''Tall Ships America''', is currently the largest [[sail training]] association in the world and a founding member of [[Sail Training International#Sail Training International|Sail Training International]].<ref>http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1123698/index.htm{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1983/05/06/obituaries/barclay-warburton-3d-dies-founder-of-tall-ships-group.html</ref>\n\nFrom her humble beginnings with only a handful of vessels sailing the [[New England]] waters, '''Tall Ships America''' has grown into an international institution with more than 250 [[tall ship]]s and [[sail training]] vessels representing 25 different countries and [[navigation|navigating]] all the [[world|world's]] [[ocean]]s.\n\nASTA was created by [[Barclay Harding Warburton III]] following his return from [[The Tall Ships' Races]] in Europe in 1972 where he joined the [[USCGC Eagle (WIX-327)|USCGC ''Eagle'']] with his [[brigantine]] ''Black Pearl'' as the first US vessels to participate in the races.\n\nA 501(c)(3) [[nonprofit]] organization, Tall Ships America's mission is to encourage character building through sail training, promote sail training to the North American public, and support education under sail.\n\n'''Tall Ships America''' organizes the '''[[Tall Ships Challenge|TALL SHIPS CHALLENGE Series]]''', a series of sail training races, rallies and maritime festivals that rotate every three years around the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] and [[Great Lakes]] Coasts of [[North America]]. In 2016, the TALL SHIPS CHALLENGE series is in the Great Lakes. In 2015, the series was on the East Coast with stops in Cape Charles, VA, Philadelphia, PA/Camden, NJ, Greenport, NY and Portland, ME.\n\n==Member ship organizations==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=23em|\n* [[Argo (yacht)]]\n* [[Balclutha (1886)]]\n* [[Bounty (1960 ship)]]\n* [[Californian (schooner)]]\n* [[Corwith Cramer (ship)]]\n* [[ARM Cuauht\u00e9moc (BE01)]]\n* [[KRI Dewaruci]]\n* [[Harvey Gamage (schooner)]]\n* [[Hawaiian Chieftain]]\n* [[Irving Johnson (ship)]]\n* [[Joseph Conrad (ship)]]\n* [[Kaisei (ship)]]\n* [[Lady Washington]]\n* [[Lynx (tall ship)]]\n* [[Ocean Star (schooner)]]\n* [[Picton Castle (ship)]]\n* [[Pilgrim (brig)]]\n* [[Pride of Baltimore]]\n* [[R. Tucker Thompson]]\n* [[Robert C. Seamans (ship)]]\n* [[Star of India (ship)]]\n* [[Stavros S Niarchos]]\n* [[HMS Surprise (replica ship)]]\n* [[Swift of Ipswich]]\n* [[Tole Mour]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sail training]]\n*[[Seamanship]]\n*[[Tall ship]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* American Sail Trainin